<section class="intro gut" data-screen-label="03 Editorial Intro">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="col-img">
      <div class="tile t-hue3 has-photo">
        <img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0522/0882/8586/files/age-early-school-light-table.png?v=1778880677&amp;width=1100" alt="Early-school children exploring translucent shapes and color at a classroom light table" loading="lazy"/>
        <span class="corner tl"></span><span class="corner tr"></span><span class="corner bl"></span><span class="corner br"></span>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="col-txt">
      <span class="eyebrow">Wonder Comes First</span>
      <h3>Wonder comes before vocabulary. <span class="it">Then comes the question.</span></h3>

      <div class="body">
        <p><span class="dropcap">A</span> child notices the way the amber catches the morning light. She turns the kaleidoscope. She turns it again. She has no word yet for refraction. She has only the question. STEAM, in this catalog, is the toolkit for that question. Birch-bark kaleidoscopes. Magnetic tiles that arch into windows. Jewel-block geometry. A wooden microscope sized for a small hand. No batteries. No instructions. Just the long, generous space between the noticing and the naming.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="pillars" style="grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);">
        <div class="p"><span class="label">To Observe</span><p>Kaleidoscope. Microscope. The first instrument.</p></div>
        <div class="p"><span class="label">To Construct</span><p>Magnetic tile. Curved arch. Tower that stands.</p></div>
        <div class="p"><span class="label">To Illuminate</span><p>Light table. Window prism. Color through glass.</p></div>
        <div class="p"><span class="label">To Investigate</span><p>The specimen study. The slow look.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

